perspectives. One group of authors examines the use of language and the meaning of concepts from an analytic point of view, the ontology of scientific terms and explores the nature of knowledge in general. Another group examines truth and types of relation. A third group of authors focuses on the current factors influencing our concept of democracy and its legal foundations and makes reference to moral aspects and the question of political responsibility. The chapters provide the reader with an overview of current philosophical problems and the answers to these questions will be decisive for future development.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aDemokratie. 4aErkenntnistheorie. 4aSprache. 4aWahrheit. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aLanguage, epistemology, truth, proof, democracy, legality.1 aAngehrn, Emil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarišić, Pavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenoist, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBermes, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaffal, Margit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaffal, Margit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGibson, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHacker, Peter M. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHüntelmann, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanzian, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Du, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarques, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/